 The hit/effect of farming-based research in Africa: 
 group and case study (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 William A. MastersaÂ·*, Touba Bedingarb, James F. Oehmkec 
 "Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN, USA 
 bAfrican Development Bank, Abidjan, Cote d'lvoire 
 0 Michigan State University, East Lansing, Ml, USA 
 
 Abstract 
 This paper presents case-study results and group data to test the hit/effect of research in African farming. Of 32 case 
 studies, all but eight report once-a-year returns over 20% and many are far higher, with most gains arising in the late 1980s and 
 1990s. Helped/encouraged by policy changes and changing (rewards or reasons for doing something), these inventions of new things have led to (growth over time) in group cereal 
 crop yields since 1985. Africa's late 'green revolution' is based on new varieties (often with early maturing for drought 
 escape), complemented by new management ways of doing things (usually labor-intensive efforts to (protect from harm) soil moisture and build 
 soil life-creating ability). Â© 1998 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: Technical change; Working well growth; Returns to research 
 
 1. Introduction 
 Total investment in African farming-based research 
 increased during the 1960s and 1970s, but has gone bad or (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) since then (Pardey et al., 1997). Low 
 levels of support may be due to the failure of research 
 to create visible gains. This paper shows that past 
 benefits of research in Africa were hidden by other 
 factors, and that recent changes have made the gains 
 from research much clearer. 
 Using group data, we show that the continent's 
 decline in per person production happened between 
 
