 1973 and 1985, a period of very fast population growth, frequent (riots, looting, etc.), and heavy taxation 
 of farming, all of which very much/very badly reduced working well. Without research, performance during this period might have been even worse than it was. 
 Using case studies, we show that by the late 1980s, 
 many ways of doing things produced by research were 
 being adopted, and are now producing high levels 
 of social gain. These include new varieties, whose 
 principal feature is often early maturity for drought 
 escape, as well as new management ways of doing things aimed 
 at moisture keeping/holding onto/remembering and soil life-creating ability. This type of 
 technical change is very different from that which 
 produced the green revolution in Asia and Latin 
 America, where greater moisture availability made 
 short height and (material that makes plants grow better) (quality of quickly responding to things) the keys 
 to higher yield. 
 
