 0.9 
 
 Although the data are limited, Africa-wide conditions can maybe best be described using FAO index 
 numbers for production, exports and imports, as 
 shown in Fig. 1. After a period of (compared to other things) good 
 performance in the 1960s, the FAO index of total 
 farming-based production per person fell regularly 
 from 1971 to 1984, for a total decline of 
 22% (from about 115 to 90). In the same period, 
 the amount/quantity of farming-based exports fell even more 
 sharply, for a total decline of over 40% (from 
 about 120 to near 70). And the amount/quantity of farming-based 
 imports rose also, more than tripling over the period 
 (from around 40 to 130). 
 The beginning of the decline in the 1972-1973 and the 
 beginning of recovery in 1985 can maybe be linked to 
 climate change, especially in the Sahel area where 
 rainfall was below long-term averages during this 
 whole period. But Africa as a whole appears to have 
 had (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) weather (Nicholson et al., 1988; Le 
 Houerou et al., 1993), so sustained farming-based weakness during the long 1971-1984 period, and later recovery must have been due to causes other 
 than climate. 
 Some clues as to the causes of farming-based spoiling are given by focusing on cereal grains. In 
 Fig. 2, we show average cereal grain yields for all 
 
