 plays a role, although sustained (popular things/general ways things are going) such as those 
 shown here are unlikely to be due to chance alone. 
 And it is important to note that group growth could 
 happen even if yields for all crops and countries are 
 constant, if production were to move/change towards higheryield crops and countries. 
 A few possible explanations could account for 
 Africa's seen/obvious success in raising group yields 
 over the past ten years. Access to markets and improved 
 (rewards or reasons for doing something) after policy changes is clearly important, as 
 is higher rainfall in some areas, reduced population 
 growth, and relative political (firm and steady nature/lasting nature/strength). But Africa's 
 success in increasing average cereal produces /gives up also points 
 to an untold story of successful technology development and move (from one place to another), as farmers adopt more and more productive seed varieties and production ways of doing things. 
 Some of the (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) watched/followed after 1984 
 involves pre-existing ways of doing things that were used more 
 intensively after policy reform changed farmers' 
 (rewards or reasons for doing something). But the mid-1980s also saw the (existing all over a large area) 
 release of new grain varieties and (producing crops/helping something grow) ways of doing things developed by African (people who work to find information) and their across-the-ocean partners. It was only in the 1970s that many 
 research programs began to focus on food crops or on 
 smallholders in not important areas, and farming-based 
 research programs often take 10 or more years to bear 
 fruit. The exact length of time of research and extension 
 effort differs/changes widely by program, but across Africa and 
 in the Sahel, the fruits of the first after-Independence 
 research programs began to reach farmers only in the 
 mid-1980s. 
 
