 3. Case studies of farming-based research hits/effects 
 To test the (thing that's given/work that's done) of research to Africa's 
 farming-based recovery and money-based growth, it is helpful to go ahead on a case-study basis, with hit/effect 
 tests of individual research programs. Since 
 1993, the authors have given training and technical 
 help to fellow workers in many national farming-based research services, and cooperated directly on a 
 number of studies across the continent. 
 In this paper, to present as large a sample of case 
 studies as possible, we provide rate-of-return guesses from other similar studies next to our 
 own research. This collection updates previous surveys of research hits/effects in Africa (Oehmke and 
 Crawford, 1996), permitting comparison with results 
 for the world as a whole (Echeverria, 1990; Evenson 
 et al., 1979). 
 Guesses from 11 analyses done before 1993 are 
 summarized in Table 1, while Table 2 summarizes the 
 results of 21 case studies completed since then. Most 
 of these 32 studies were never published, as they were 
 written for and circulated among an audience of 
 specialists in a particular country. Maybe the most 
 striking result of this collection is that, of the 32 
 studies we found, only 8 report rates of return below 
 20%-and the costs of these relative failures would be 
 more than offset by the many cases of very high 
 returns. 
 The research programs talked about in these studies 
 may not be a random sample of research activity, but 
 
