 they cover programs facing heavy criticism, as well as 
 those seen as successful, and include a broad crosssection of the major types of research programs. Our 
 collection confirms that returns to research in Africa 
 are almost the same  those found in other places, showing high payoffs for a wide range of programs. The (thing that's given/work that's done) of 
 research to farming-based performance and money-based 
 growth is not obvious, since it happens slowly, and is 
 spread widely across the population, but the net 
 benefits are significantly larger than the money/giving money (to) gave/given. 
 A striking result from our collection is that the 
 research failures are often-but not always-in the 
 hardest agroecological areas. A few competing guesses could explain this result. The first and 
 maybe most in control/most common view is that payoffs tend to be lower 
 in lower-possible areas because (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)'s 
 low reserves of soil and water limit any possible 
 production increases. A second and more detailed 
 view would be that those working well-improving 
 
 inventions of new things, which are discovered in these areas, 
 are limited in their (ability to be used for something), due to the (many different kinds of people or things) of 
 micro-(surrounding conditions) found in low-rainfall areas. A 
 third explanation would involve the political-(process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 problems of these areas, where weak governments are 
 often unable to provide key public products (that are bought and sold). But all of 
 these guesses are argued by the sustained 
 yield increases watched/followed for the Sahel in Figs. 2 and 3 
 above, which shows that sustained working well 
 growth is possible even in that very harsh (surrounding conditions). 
 Maybe the most interesting general explanation 
 for some programs' failure is simply that local institutions had not (yet) found the right mix of activities to 
 produce (producing a lot for a given amount of money) technologies in those locations. 
 For example, on Table 1, the very low rate of return to 
 research in Niger found by Mazzucato and Ly (1992) 
 can be connected with that country's very weak seedmultiplication system, which effectively prevented the 
 (existing all over a large area) spreading around of new varieties. On 
 
 W.A. Masters et at./Agricultural Money flow 19 (1998) 81-86 
 
 Table 2, the (compared to other things) low gains from a project to 
 (help increase/show in a good way) stone dikes in Burkina Paso recorded/supported by 
 Ouedraogo and Illy (1996) can be connected with that 
 project's provision of credit to farmers for the (instance of buying something for money) of rock phosphate to go with the stone dikes, 
 which accounted for a big part of the project's costs, but may have added/have given little to its 
 benefits. In these and other cases, described/explained hit/effect 
 tests provide key lessons for the design of 
 future projects, but provide no (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that research 
 itself is unproductive. In fact, (even though there is the existence of) the late start and 
 occasional failures of Africa's foodcrop research programs, case studies provide (enough information or physical objects that clearly prove something) that highimpact inventions of new things are now newly appearing in all of Africa's 
 agroclimatic zones. 
 
 85 
 
 Mrican research, like almost the same  efforts in other places, does 
 yield great money-based gains in terms of the level and 
 (firm and steady nature/lasting nature/strength) of farmers' income, and in terms of national 
 money-based growth. 
 
