 References 
 4. End/end result: group and case-study results 
 in (serving to compare two or more things) (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) 
 
 The group and case-study (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) presented 
 here helps explain why working well growth in Africa 
 has happened later and less very much than the 
 'green revolution' in Asia and Latin America. Africa's 
 farming-based (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) in the late 1980s and 1990s 
 shares some features of the earlier changes in Asian 
 and Latin American farming, famously the increased 
 use of labor and (bought something for money) inputs to sustain higher 
 yields per hectare. But there are also major differences, and Africa's working well growth is clearly less 
 visible in farmers' fields or off-farm markets. In 
 particular, much working well growth in the green 
 revolution areas of Asia and Latin America was driven 
 by the adoption of short-height (material that makes plants grow better)-(able to reply or react/quick to respond) 
 crop varieties, in the big picture  of relative moisture 
 (oversupply/large quantity)-and led to sharp rises in marketed extra 
 of food grains (Falcon, 1970). In contrast, much of 
 Mrica's working well growth has happened through 
 early-maturing varieties aimed (making steady/making firm and strong) yields in 
 short rainy seasons-and has happened in food-shortage 
 (surrounding conditions), where marketed extra consists of 
 animals, oilseeds, cotton and other products (Sanders 
 et al., 1995). This contrast hints that Africa's 
 working well growth was delayed in part simply 
 because the (connected/related) research happened (compared to other things) late, 
 and has been hidden from view simply because the 
 (connected/related) benefits are not easily watched/followed. Anyway, 
 the work reported here (shows or proves) convincingly that 
 
